  "prompt": "What are examples of prefixes and suffixes?",
  "response": "Prefixes and suffixes are common elements added to the beginning or end of a word to modify its meaning or function. Here are some examples of each:\n\n### Prefixes\nPrefixes are added to the beginning of a word. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. **un-** (not): unhappy, uncertain\n2. **re-** (again): redo, revisit\n3. **pre-** (before): prehistoric, preview\n4. **mis-** (wrongly): misunderstand, misplace\n5. **dis-** (opposite of): disagree, disconnect\n6. **in-** (not or into): inactive, inject\n7. **sub-** (under or below): submarine, substandard\n8. **inter-** (between): international, interconnect\n9. **hyper-** (excessive): hypertension, hyperactive\n10. **anti-** (against): antidote, antifreeze\n\n### Suffixes\nSuffixes are added to the end of a word. Here are some examples:\n\n1. **-ing** (action or process): running, jumping\n2. **-ed** (past tense): walked, finished\n3. **-ly** (in a certain way): quickly, softly\n4. **-ness** (state or quality): happiness, darkness\n5. **-ful** (full of): beautiful, helpful\n6. **-less** (without): hopeless, fearless\n7. **-able / -ible** (capable of): manageable, visible\n8. **-ment** (result or condition): development, enjoyment\n9. **-tion / -sion** (the act of): education, decision\n10. **-er / -or** (one who does): teacher, creator\n\nThese prefixes and suffixes help to expand the vocabulary and change the meanings of base words to convey more specific concepts.",
